                <p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Geometric distribution</strong></=
b><span> is a probability distribution that defines the number of trials re=
quired to get the first success in a series of independent and identically =
distributed </span><b><strong>Bernoulli trials,</strong></b><span> where ea=
ch trial has </span><b><strong>two possible outcomes: success or failure.</=
strong></b><span> The trials are conducted </span><b><strong>until the firs=
t success is observed,</strong></b><span> and the </span><b><strong>probabi=
lity of success in each trial is constant.</strong></b></p><p dir=3D"ltr" s=
tyle=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>The geometric distribution is commonly =
used in various real-life circumstances. In the financial industry, it is u=
sed to estimate the financial rewards of making a given decision in a cost-=
benefit analysis.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span> Geometric distributions a=
re </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/probability-distri=
bution/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span>probability distributions=
 </span></a><span>that are based on three key assumptions.</span></p><ul><l=
i value=3D"1"><span>Trials are independent</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span=
>Each trial has one of two outcomes: success or failure</span></li><li valu=
e=3D"3"><span>For each trial, the probability of success, p, is constant ac=
ross trials.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"geometric-distribution-formula" styl=
e=3D"text-align:left"><span>Geometric Distribution Formulas</span></h2><p d=
ir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>The geometric distribution =
is characterized by two important functions: the </span><b><strong>Probabil=
ity Mass Function (PMF)</strong></b><span> and the </span><b><strong>Cumula=
tive Distribution Function (CDF)</strong></b><span>. These formulas help ca=
lculate the likelihood of achieving the first success after a certain numbe=
r of trials. Below are the key formulas associated with the geometric distr=
ibution:</span></p><figure class=3D"image"><img src=3D"https://media.geeksf=
orgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20241204174005309209/Geometric-Distribution-=
formulas.webp" alt=3D"Geometric-Distribution-formulas" width=3D"800" height=
=3D"400"><figcaption>Geometric Distribution Formulas</figcaption></figure><=
p><br></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Desktop_InContent_ATF_728x280" style=3D"text-al=
ign: center; margin: 10px 0px;"></div><h3 id=3D"geometric-distribution-pmf"=
 style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Geometric Distribution PMF</strong></=
b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>The likelihood that a discrete random variable,=
 X, will be exactly identical to some value, x, is determined by the </span=
><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/probability-mass-function/#=
:~:text=3DProbability%20Density%20Function-,What%20is%20Probability%20Mass%=
20Function%3F,calculate%20the%20probability%20mass%20function." target=3D"_=
self" rel=3D"noopener"><span>probability mass function.</span></a></p><bloc=
kquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: center;"><b><strong>P (X =3D x) =
=3D (1 - p)</strong></b><b><sup><strong>x -1</strong></sup></b><b><strong>p=
</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>where, 0 &lt; p =E2=
=89=A4 1.</strong></b></p><h3 id=3D"geometric-distribution-cdf" style=3D"te=
xt-align:left"><b><strong>Geometric Distribution CDF</strong></b></h3><p di=
r=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: justify;"><span>The probability that a</span=
><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/random-variable/" target=3D"_blan=
k" rel=3D"noopener"><span> random variable, </span></a><span>X, will assume=
 a value that is less than or equal to x can be described as the cumulative=
 distribution function of a random variable, X, that is assessed at a point=
, x. The distribution function is another name for it.</span></p><blockquot=
e><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: center;"><b><strong>P(X =E2=89=A4 x) =
=3D 1 - (1 - p)</strong></b><b><sup><strong>x</strong></sup></b></p></block=
quote><h3 id=3D"mean-of-geometric-distribution" style=3D"text-align:left"><=
b><strong>Mean of Geometric Distribution</strong></b></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><s=
pan>The geometric distribution's mean is also the geometric distribution's =
expected value. The weighted average of all values of a random variable, X,=
 is the expected value of X.</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"=
text-align: center;"><b><strong>E[X] =3D 1 / p</strong></b></p></blockquote=
><h3 id=3D"variance-of-geometric-distribution" style=3D"text-align:left"><b=
